    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-03-10T19:06:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-03-10T19:06:00-05:00" n="117"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                <head>117. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassies in All <gloss target="#t_OECD1">OECD</gloss>
                        Capitals</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d117fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 3 <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss>.
                        Secret. Drafted on March 10 by <persName corresp="#p_BGS1">Brown</persName>;
                        cleared in <gloss target="#t_NEAARP1">NEA/ARP</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_AFN1">AF/N</gloss> (in substance), <gloss target="#t_EURRPE1"
                            >EUR/RPE</gloss>; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_KJL1"
                            >Katz</persName>. Repeated to <gloss target="#t_USEC1">USEC</gloss>
                        Brussels, <gloss target="#t_USNATO1">USNATO</gloss> Brussels, Algiers,
                        Beirut, Dhahran, Kuwait, Jidda, Djakarta, Benghazi, Caracas, Lagos, and
                        Tripoli. Printed from an unsigned copy.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-03-11T00:06:00+00:00">March 11, 1972,
                        0006Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42129. <gloss target="#t_subj1">Subj</gloss>: Petroleum: <gloss
                        target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> Accepts <gloss target="#t_Participation1"
                        >Participation</gloss> Principle. <gloss target="#t_Ref1">Ref</gloss>: State
                    40217 (Notal); State 38469.<note n="2" xml:id="d117fn2">In telegram 40217 to
                        Jidda and London, March 7, the Embassy reported that <gloss
                            target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> owners were preparing to send a
                        letter to the Saudi Government advising that they would accept <persName
                            corresp="#p_FIAAA2">Faisal</persName>’s principle of 20 percent <gloss
                            target="#t_Participation1">participation</gloss>. (Ibid.) In telegram
                        38469 to all <gloss target="#t_OECD1">OECD</gloss> capitals, March 8, the
                        Department summarized the status of the <gloss target="#t_OPEC1"
                            >OPEC</gloss>-oil company negotiations. (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Parent companies of <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> have advised
                        Department that <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> President
                            <persName corresp="#p_JF1">Jungers</persName> informed Saudi Petroleum
                        Minister <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1">Yamani</persName>, on March 10 in
                        Beirut, that company prepared accept principle of twenty percent <gloss
                            target="#t_Participation1">participation</gloss> in <gloss
                            target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss>, as requested by King <persName
                            corresp="#p_FIAAA2">Faisal</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d117fn3">As
                            reported in telegram 771 from Jidda, March 7. (Ibid.)</note>
                        <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> however reserved its position on
                        timing, compensation, amount of compensation, disposition of government’s
                        share of production, future financing requirements, and desire for
                        assurances for future.</item>
                    <pb facs="0325" n="287" xml:id="pg_287"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> decision has come after failure of
                        owners’ efforts, through appeal to King <persName corresp="#p_FIAAA2"
                            >Faisal</persName>, to block <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1"
                            >Yamani</persName>’s <gloss target="#t_Participation1"
                            >participation</gloss> push. Faced with King’s insistence that companies
                        accept principle of <gloss target="#t_Participation1">participation</gloss>,
                        and some indication that Saudis prepared to show flexibility on terms,
                        companies apparently saw no choice but to accede. They secured agreement of
                        other international oil companies in meeting of <gloss
                            target="#t_LondonPolicyGroup1">London Policy Group</gloss> on March 9 in
                        New York. They also agreed to inform major consuming governments immediately
                        after giving letter to <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1">Yamani</persName>.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Although long and perhaps bitter negotiations remain with Saudi Arabia and
                        other oil producers, Rubicon has been crossed. While it obviously impossible
                        to predict how companies’ new course will work out, we consider their
                        decision was correct and that they have chosen least undesirable alternative
                        open to them.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1">Yamani</persName> agreed to make press
                        announcement March 11 before opening of <gloss target="#t_OPEC1"
                            >OPEC</gloss> conference in which he, speaking as Saudi Oil Minister,
                        would announce companies’ decision and state that complicated negotiating
                        process due to start soon. Companies will also release press statements in
                        New York. <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1">Yamani</persName> told <persName
                            corresp="#p_JF1">Jungers</persName> that Council of Ministers had
                        already arranged <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> resolution; it
                        unclear whether it will now be changed to reflect new <gloss
                            target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss> position.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Next <gloss target="#t_ARAMCO1">Aramco</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                            >SAG</gloss> meeting tentatively set for March 18. <persName
                            corresp="#p_JF1">Jungers</persName> informed <persName corresp="#p_YAZ1"
                            >Yamani</persName>, and latter accepted, that companies would be
                        prepared only to discuss agenda for subsequent meetings.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
